{{distinguish|Bassari language (Togo)}} {{Infobox language | name = Basari | nativename = Oniyan | states = [[Guinea]], [[Senegal]] | ethnicity = [[Bassari people|Bassari]] | speakers = 33,600 | date = 2014-2015 | ref = <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/bsc|title=Oniyan|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-11|language=en}}</ref> | familycolor = Niger-Congo | fam2 = [[Atlantic–Congo languages|Atlantic–Congo]] | fam3 = [[Atlantic languages|Atlantic]] | fam4 = [[Senegambian languages|Senegambian]] | fam5 = [[Tenda languages|Tenda]] | fam6 = Basari–Bedik | minority = {{flag|Senegal}} | iso3 = bsc | glotto = bass1258 | glottorefname = Bassari }} {{infobox ethnonym|aliyan|biliyan|oniyan|Liyan}} '''Basari''', or '''Oniyan''' (Onian, Onëyan, Ayan, Biyan, Wo), is a [[Senegambian language]] of [[Senegal]] and [[Guinea]] spoken by the [[Bassari people]], who are traditional [[hunter-gatherer]]s.
== Writing system ==
This is the writing system of Senegal:
