{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}} {{short description|cyberbullying campaign in the United States}} [[File:Be Best Campaign.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]] with students in the [[Oval Office]] at the announcement of the initiative]]
'''Be Best''' is a public awareness campaign promoted by United States First Lady [[Melania Trump]], focusing on well-being for youth, and advocating against [[cyberbullying]] and drug (particularly [[opioid]]) use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/politics/article/Melania-Trump-launches-BE-BEST-awareness-12894525.php|title=Melania Trump launches 'BE BEST' awareness campaign for kids|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Rhodan |first=Maya |url=http://time.com/5268266/be-best-first-lady-melania-trump-launches-official-white-house-project/ |title=Melania Trump Launches 'Be Best' to Focus on Cyberbullying |work=Time |date=May 7, 2018 |accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref>
==History== Melania Trump made the initiative as a way to address online behavior and the opioid crisis, and came with the name "Be Best". Her husband [[Donald Trump]] reportedly tried to persuade her to change topics so she could avoid dealing with [[Donald Trump on social media|his own Twitter habits]], but Mrs. Trump said she was willing to face any criticism.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rogers |first1=Katie |last2=Davis |first2=Julie Hirschfeld |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/17/us/politics/melania-trump-first-lady.html |title=Melania Trump, a Mysterious First Lady, Weathers a Chaotic White House |work=The New York Times |date=August 17, 2018 |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wise |first=Justin |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/402435-trump-didnt-want-melanias-platform-to-be-anti-bullying-initiative |title=Trump tried to dissuade Melania from 'Be Best' anti-bullying campaign: report |date=August 17, 2018 |work=The Hill |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> She formally introduced the campaign on May 7, 2018. Following her speech in the [[White House Rose Garden]], President [[Donald Trump]] signed a [[Presidential proclamation (United States)|proclamation]] declaring May 7 "Be Best" day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-44034723|title=Melania Trump unveils 'Be Best' campaign|date=May 7, 2018|work=''BBC News''|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/melania-trump-platform/|title=Melania Trump speaks: Live updates|date=May 7, 2018|publisher=CNN|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2018/05/07/melania-trump-unveils-be-best-initiative-to-help-kids.html|title=Melania Trump unveils ‘Be Best’ initiative to help kids|last=Pappas|first=Alex|date=May 7, 2018|publisher=Fox News Channel|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> Unlike policy initiatives by previous first ladies (such as [[Michelle Obama]]'s [[Let's Move!]] campaign against childhood obesity, or [[Nancy Reagan]]'s [[Just Say No]] to drugs campaign), Be Best is broad in scope. The initiative focuses on physical and emotional well-being, and also advocates against [[cyberbullying]] and [[opioid abuse]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCammon |first1=Sarah |title=First Lady Melania Trump Unveils 'Be Best' Campaign, Focusing On Children |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/05/07/609180852/first-lady-melania-trump-unveils-be-best-campaign-focusing-on-children |accessdate=July 31, 2018 |publisher=NPR |date=May 7, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>
The initiative began with a slow start, as Mrs. Trump underwent kidney surgery one week after the campaign was launched. She made no public appearances for the next several weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCammon |first1=Sarah |title=One Month Later, What's Become Of Melania Trump's 'Be Best' Campaign? |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/06/07/617642736/1-month-later-whats-become-of-melania-trumps-be-best-campaign |accessdate=July 31, 2018 |publisher=NPR |date=June 7, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> On July 24, 2018, she visited the [[Monroe Carell Jr. Children's Hospital at Vanderbilt]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] and talked about children with [[neonatal withdrawal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/07/24/politics/melania-trump-be-best-nashville/index.html |title=Melania Trump pushes 'Be Best' initiative with trip to Nashville |publisher=CNN |date=July 24, 2018 |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> On August 6, 2018, she tweeted, "It's #Backtoschool for many youth this month. As you begin a new year, how will you be the best you? #BeBest".<ref>{{cite web |last=Stewart |first=Chelsea |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/melania-trumps-back-to-school-tweet-about-be-best-totally-backfired-10035042 |title=Melania Trump's Tweet About "Be Best" Back-To-School Tips Totally Backfired |work=Elite Daily |date=August 8, 2018 |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref> She held a cyberbullying summit outside [[Washington, D.C.]] on August 20, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last=Phelps |first=Jordyn |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/lady-melania-trump-speaks-cyberbullying/story?id=57284988 |title=First lady Melania Trump speaks out against cyberbullying |date=August 20, 2018 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=August 20, 2018}}</ref>
==Criticism== The campaign was accompanied by a booklet that was promoted as having been written "by First Lady Melania Trump and the [[Federal Trade Commission]]" (FTC), but it was nearly identical to a document prepared by the commission in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/may/07/melania-trump-plagiarism-row-be-best-campaign|title=Melania Trump in new plagiarism row over online safety pamphlet|last=Smith|first=David|date=May 8, 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref> The similarities prompted accusations of plagiarism, to which her office responded by admonishing the press for reporting on the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/us/politics/melania-trump-plagiarism-be-best-initiative.html|title=As Melania Trump Faces Plagiarism Claims, Her Staff Lashes Out at News Media|date=May 8, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 8, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following the plagiarism accusations the White House's website changed the copy to read "a Federal Trade Commission booklet, promoted by First Lady Melania Trump"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/386641-melania-be-best-campaign-booklet-copies-from-obama-era-ftc-brochure|title=Melania Trump 'Be Best' pamphlet was first published by Obama's FTC|last=Seipel|first=Brooke|date=May 8, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>
The fact checking site [[Snopes]] found the charge of plagiarism "Mostly False" saying, "Melania Trump did not claim she had written the pamphlet herself, and she contributed an introduction to a slightly revised version of the booklet. The FTC was always credited for the creation of the booklet and supported its inclusion in the First Lady's "Be Best" campaign."<ref>{{cite web |title=Did Melania Trump Plagiarize a Pamphlet for the ‘Be Best’ Campaign? |url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/did-melania-trump-plagiarize-pamphlet/ |website=Snopes |accessdate=August 21, 2018}}</ref>
